# Sorot UI Rules
- You are an expert in Vue 3, Vite, TypeScript, and Tailwind CSS.
- Always use `<script setup lang="ts">` and Composition API.
- Do NOT use Options API.
- For reactivity, prefer `ref` over `reactive` unless grouping a complex object.
- Strictly type all props, emits, and API responses. No `any` types allowed.
- Follow Gestalt principles for UI/UX. Use standard Tailwind utility classes.
- If handling eye-tracking data arrays, prioritize performance and avoid deep watching large arrays unless necessary.

## Tech Stack
- Framework: Vue 3 (Composition API with `<script setup>`)
- Build Tool: Vite
- Language: TypeScript (Strict mode enabled)
- State Management: Pinia
- Styling: Tailwind CSS

## Core Constraints
- CLIENT-SIDE ONLY: All video processing, algorithm execution, and CSV generation MUST occur locally in the browser. Do not write any Node.js backend logic.
- PERFORMANCE: Heavy computer vision extraction or frame-by-frame processing must use Web Workers to prevent UI freezing.
- ACCURACY: Gaze extraction algorithms must account for a ~15px margin of error.

## Coding Style
- Use descriptive, explicit variable names (e.g., `gazeCoordinates` instead of `coords`).
- Extract complex UI elements into modular, reusable Vue components.
- Strongly type all data structures, especially for X/Y coordinates and ROI boundaries.